ce:section.ce:para:
All voltammetric measurements were made in a cell containing 10mL phosphate buffer solution (pH 4.7, 0.1M) using modified electrodes. The test solution was added into the cell after recording the blank run. The test analyte was allowed to accumulate at +0.1V (accumulation potential, E

                           acc
                        ), for 90s (accumulation time, t

                           acc
                        ), under dynamic condition followed by equilibration for 15s. Differential pulse anodic stripping voltammetry (DPASV) runs of analyte were recorded in the potential range varying from −0.1 to +0.4V, at a scan rate 10 mVs−1, pulse amplitude 25mV, and pulse width 50ms. Cyclic voltammetry (CV) experiments were performed in the potential window −0.2 to +0.6V at various scan rates (10–200mVs−1) in anodic stripping mode. Since oxygen did not influence the voltammetry in the anodic potential window studied for the oxidative stripping of analyte, any de-aeration of the cell content was not necessary. This was confirmed by recording DPASV runs, with and without nitrogen purging that revealed similar response in both conditions. All DPASV runs for each concentration of test analyte could be quantified using the method of standard addition. The limit of detection (LOD, 3σ) was calculated as three times the standard deviation from the blank measurement (in the absence of template) divided by the slope of the calibration plot between analyte concentration and current [For details, vide Supporting data Section S.4 and Fig. S1].
